### Classes

TypeScript classes extend JavaScript classes with type annotations, access modifiers, and more.

### Basic Class

```typescript
class Person {
  name: string;
  age: number;

  constructor(name: string, age: number) {
    this.name = name;
    this.age = age;
  }

  greet(): string {
    return `Hello, I'm ${this.name}`;
  }
}

const alice = new Person("Alice", 30);
console.log(alice.greet());
```

### Property Initialization

TypeScript requires properties to be initialized:

```typescript
class Point {
  x: number = 0;
  y: number = 0;

  constructor(x?: number, y?: number) {
    if (x !== undefined) this.x = x;
    if (y !== undefined) this.y = y;
  }
}
```

### Parameter Properties

TypeScript provides shorthand for declaring and initializing properties from constructor parameters:

```typescript
class Person {
  constructor(
    public name: string,
    public age: number
  ) {}
  // Properties name and age are automatically created
}
```

### Methods

```typescript
class Calculator {
  add(a: number, b: number): number {
    return a + b;
  }

  subtract(a: number, b: number): number {
    return a - b;
  }
}
```

> **Key Point:** Parameter properties with access modifiers (`public`, `private`, `protected`) create and initialize properties automatically.

codeExample:
class Product {
  constructor(
    public id: number,
    public name: string,
    public price: number
  ) {}

  applyDiscount(percent: number): void {
    this.price = this.price * (1 - percent / 100);
  }

  getInfo(): string {
    return `${this.name}: $${this.price.toFixed(2)}`;
  }
}

const laptop = new Product(1, "Laptop", 999.99);
laptop.applyDiscount(10);
console.log(laptop.getInfo()); // Laptop: $899.99
